2.  They are finally complying with the agreements they signed and agreed to over 10 years ago.<br>
a. Because they saw the error of their ways, and have changed.<br>
b. Because of the sanctions placed on them, can no longer pursue their goals.<br>
<br>
I'm betting on 2b, personally.<br>
<br>
What brought NK to the decision to make their actions public?<br>
<br>
They saw the US wrapped up with the Iraq/Terrorism/Afghanistan/Pakistan situation.  How could we handle another?  With our plate so full, it's an excellent oppurtunity for them to &quot;renegotiate&quot; their contract with us.  They are the ones creating the pressure there, not us.  We were FINE with how things were in NK.  Sure they weren't perfect, but far better than they are now.<br>
<br>
Also, what exactly can we do against North Korea?  We had shipments of Oil or something to them right?  Ok, we stopped those over a month ago, right?  What is left to what we could do?  Ask them politely to stop?  Why would they, what reasons do they have to do so?  Have they made their &quot;demands&quot; public?  There is all kind of talk about them wanting &quot;dialogue&quot;.  To talk about what?  They want MORE appeasment.  They are using their nuclear program like a gun to our heads.  It's a threat, and we all know that.  Nukes aren't built primarily for DEFENSE, like Merton has suggested.  They are offensive weapons.  The only time that a country would use a nuke for defensive purposes is if they are loosing or about to loose a war.  Where they would need to nuke an invading army.  Who has threatened to invade North Korea?  No one.  They are the ones that have been thumping their chests for almost a half century towards South Korea.  They do it so often the South Koreans have gotten use to them to the point that the threats are ignored.<br>
<br>
North Korea has one card to play, in order to get MORE support from the international community.  They are playing it.<br>
<br>
What is there to do about North Korea?<br>
<br>
Loegan, I know you're not a &quot;Dove&quot;.<br>
<br>
