<br>
- As you pointed out, we had normalized relations with Iraq in the 1980s because our eye was on the dangers of Iran.  Why was Iran a danger at the time, their fundamental support of terrorism against the West.  You're right, the enemy of our enemy is our friend.... till that enemy is no longer the threat it use to be.  We didn't turn a blind eye to the gassing of his people because we had no qualms over the actions.  We ignored it, because we had bigger fish to fry.  To have done something back then would have ruined the goals we had at the time, that of the interior collapse of Iran.<br>
<br>
It's the whole, deciding to go with the lesser of two evils at the time, kind of thing.<br>
<br>
No I don't believe that Kuwait showed him to be a threat to us, persay.  It showed him to be a threat to the region.  The world's economy is tied into that region.  So not only was it justified to go in and stop him because he was violating national law in his invasion, it was also justified because we were protecting the economy from a madman.  Having Saddam in control of Kuwaiti oil would have made the position of an &quot;evil&quot; country (IE actions taking in the 1980s against his own people) all that much stronger.<br>
<br>
So with Kuwait, Saddam rose himself to become the biggest piece of shit that needed to be dealt with.  Since we weren't occuppied with the problems from Iran any longer, he was no longer needed.  Therefore, it's his time to go.<br>
<br>
Also, the times have changed.  Back when Iraq was gassing their people, we didn't have the level of terrorist activity pointed against us.  So no, the idea of WMD being used against us wasn't the big threat.  Now the possibility of terrorists either being given, or stealing the weapons is something that we no longer wish to be a possibility.  Remove the weapons, remove the threat.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Who will blame N Korea for taking Bush under the currnt climate? Not many. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You're completely correct.  Bush's stance on North Korea, and his chest thumping did help their current stance.  But just because people like to back the little dog, especially when the big dog is the US, doesn't make the actions of the little dog right.  North Korea, though playing the hand they've been dealt, isn't the peaceful one in the situation.  The US is.  The US government along with the rest of the nuclear powers, backed with the knowledge of the past 50 years, have all been trying to keep nuclear weapons out of the hands of new countries.<br>
<br>
I know some may enjoy to claim that allowing the Koreans to have nukes will &quot;even the playing field somewhat&quot;, but that's just bullshit.  North Korea isn't a little shit country because the US has nukes.  They know that they are safe from any kind of nuclear assault from the West.  Everyone can be assured that the West has no desire to unleash another nuke upon another country.<br>
<br>
The only way our nukes would be a threat to another country, is if that country had the ability to attack the US and cripple it, to its very shores.  Does North Korea have this ability?  No.  Even if they did, such an undertaking would be so enormous, and against international law, why should anyone but an enemy of the US want to allow North Korea the ability to do such a thing?<br>
<br>
I'm not saying you are an enemy of the US Loegan, I'm just unfolding the consequences of things if they were allowed to just happen.  There are really two pretty simple core reasons why North Korea and Iraq need to be dealt with.<br>
<br>
Iraq - They've been violating mandates agreed upon and given to them by the UN for over 10 years.  Times have changed to the point, that the reasons and the goals behind our insistance that Iraq must comply, have changed enough to the point that we can't give Iraq another 10 years of non-compliance.<br>
<br>
North Korea - They have violated agreements and negotiated in bad faith since almost the start of negotiations back in the 1990s.  Their possessing nuclear weapons will bring no good to the world, and will actually bring more harm.  Either they will uses the weapons as a threat over the world's head, essentially mugging the world, or their weapons could slip into the hands of an enemy of the US (terrorists) which would use the weapon upon the US, or World.  With North Korea's broken economy, just how easy do you think it would be to bribe its leaders into handing over such weapons?  Look at Russia, and our worries over their &quot;misplacement&quot; of their nukes, for an example. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094" target="top">Wenin Huirunda</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
